para_trans: 2. The said order comes into force with immediate effect and the aforesaid officer shall immediately join the post indicated in the transfer. The date on which the officers concerned appeared at the place of the new appointment should be immediately communicated to the Government by e-mail / post. Orders regarding the appointment of Mr. Akshay Poyam and Mr. Kailash Pawar shall be issued separately.

3. The officers concerned shall be liable for disciplinary action under the provisions of the Representation of the People Act, 1950 and the Maharashtra Civil Services (Conduct of Business) Rules, 1979, if they are found not to have joined the place of transfer before the expiry of the period of assumption of office in accordance with the said provision under Rule 15 of the Maharashtra Civil Services (Period of Retirement, Non-Service and Provisions during Suspension, Dismissal and Removal from Service) Rules, 1981.

The officer concerned shall take care to join the place of posting within the prescribed period as per the rules of the Maharashtra Civil Services (Period of assumption of office, non-serving service and period of suspension, dismissal and removal from service) Rules, 1981 or else, if he fails to join the post of this post, his absence shall be deemed to be "non-working day" (/). 7 €5. 7071) shall be deemed to be so, 5. Leave of the officer concerned shall not be granted on any ground except with the previous sanction of the Government. Also, as per Rule-30 (c) of the Maharashtra Civil Services (Leave) Rules, 1981, no leave applications of officers transferred by the original office shall be entertained. If such applications are received, they should be returned by post to the concerned authorities at the original address.

6. The concerned shall note that in case of non-acceptance of appointment immediately under the said order or attempt to cancel transfer under any kind of pressure, disciplinary action shall be taken against them on the ground that the act violates Rule 23 of the Maharashtra Civil Services (Conduct) Rules, 1979, treating it as misconduct.
